                    <p style="font-size: 1.4em; line-height: 1.6;">"I aimed at the public's heart, and by accident I hit it in the stomach."</p>
                    <div class="primary-source-attribution">‚Äî Upton Sinclair, reflecting on <em>The Jungle</em> (1906)</div>
                </div>
                <p style="margin-top: 2em; font-size: 1.1em; color: #aaa;">By the end of today, you'll understand why that quote captures everything about this movement.</p>

                <aside class="notes">
                    <h4>üìö What You Need to Know</h4>
                    <p>This is our hook. Don't explain the quote yet. Let it sit. Students will encounter <em>The Jungle</em> later in the lecture, and by then they'll understand exactly what Sinclair meant. The quote captures the central tension of Progressive reform: reformers often cared deeply about injustice, but the public only responded when they felt personally threatened.</p>

                    <h4>üí≠ Context & Connections</h4>
                    <p>Sinclair was a socialist who spent seven weeks undercover in Chicago's meatpacking plants. He wrote <em>The Jungle</em> to expose the exploitation of immigrant workers. Readers ignored the labor conditions and fixated on the contaminated food. The result: consumer protection legislation passed within months, while labor reform took decades.</p>
                </aside>
            </section>

