            <section>
                <h2>From Last Time</h2>
                <p style="font-size: 1.15em; font-style: italic; margin-bottom: 1em;">"The city could not survive without collective action."</p>
                <p>Sanitary reformers built a template:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><span class="key-term">Investigation</span> ‚Äî mapping disease to find causes</li>
                    <li><span class="key-term">Expertise</span> ‚Äî public health officials as authorities</li>
                    <li><span class="key-term">Government intervention</span> ‚Äî crisis justified state power</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top: 1.2em;">Today: that template goes <span class="key-term">national</span>.</p>

                <aside class="notes">
                    <h4>üìö What You Need to Know</h4>
                    <p>This slide connects today's lecture to the Chapter 20 urbanization unit. Students learned that cholera and typhoid epidemics forced Americans to accept that health was a public responsibility, not a private matter. Sanitary reformers built boards of health, hired inspectors, and used data to justify government intervention. That was the blueprint for Progressivism.</p>

                    <h4>üí≠ Context & Connections</h4>
                    <p>The Skocpol framework from Chapter 20: crisis creates capacity. Government grew not from ideology but from practical necessity. The same pattern repeats here: crisis (corruption, exploitation, contamination) creates intervention (regulation, inspection, legislation) creates institutionalization (permanent agencies, expanded federal power). Spend a moment here verbally reminding students of the cholera and typhoid material ‚Äî the slide is deliberately spare so your voice carries the connection.</p>
                </aside>
            </section>


            <!-- ========== SLIDE 4: Transition ========== -->
            <section>
                <h2>But First: Who Had the Resources to Reform?</h2>
                <p style="font-size: 1.1em; margin-bottom: 1em;">Movements don't just happen. They require people with <span class="key-term">time</span>, <span class="key-term">training</span>, and <span class="key-term">frustration</span>.</p>
                <p>Before we define Progressivism, we need to understand the class of people who made it possible.</p>

                <aside class="notes">
                    <h4>üìö What You Need to Know</h4>
                    <p>This is a structural question, not a narrative one. We're not asking "what happened?" but "why was this movement possible when it was?" The answer has to do with material changes in American society ‚Äî specifically the explosion of higher education, the rise of credentialed professions, and the growth of a salaried middle class that was distinct from both the industrial elite and the working poor.</p>
