<section>
  <h2 style="margin-bottom: 8px;">Big Systems and Big Problems (1870‚Äì1920)</h2>

  <p style="font-size:0.96em; max-width: 860px; line-height:1.22; margin: 0 auto 12px auto;">
    Industrial capitalism did not just add factories. It built large-scale systems such as corporations,
    rail networks, mass retail, and rapidly growing cities.
  </p>

  <ul style="font-size:0.96em; line-height:1.22; max-width: 860px; margin: 0 auto;">
    <li><strong>Scale:</strong> railroads and corporations coordinate people, money, and goods across distance</li>
    <li><strong>Urban growth:</strong> cities swell and strain housing, sanitation, transit, policing, and schools</li>
    <li><strong>Politics under pressure:</strong> machine politics and patronage thrive in fast-growing cities</li>
    <li><strong>A new kind of crisis:</strong> problems increasingly look systemic rather than individual</li>
  </ul>

  <p style="margin: 12px auto 0 auto; font-size:0.94em; max-width: 860px; line-height:1.22;">
    <strong>Core idea:</strong> when life runs through systems, problems look like failures of systems.
  </p>

  <aside class="notes">
    Frame this as the setup: modern life becomes organized through large systems, so reform becomes about redesigning systems.
    Avoid listing specific reforms yet. Build the need for reform.
  </aside>
</section>


