            <section>
                <h2>The Rise of the Professions</h2>
                <p>New professional associations set standards and built <span class="popup-trigger" data-popup="gatekeeping-popup">gatekeeping systems</span>:</p>
                <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 1em; margin-top: 1em; font-size: 0.85em;">
                    <div class="concept-card">
                        <h4>American Medical Association</h4>
                        <p>All-white, all-male at the turn of the century</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="concept-card">
                        <h4>American Bar Association</h4>
                        <p>All-white, all-male at the turn of the century</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="concept-card">
                        <h4>American Historical Association</h4>
                        <p>All-white, all-male at the turn of the century</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="concept-card">
                        <h4>American Economic Association</h4>
                        <p>All-white, all-male at the turn of the century</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <p style="margin-top: 1em;">These organizations professionalized American life ‚Äî but they also <span class="key-term">excluded</span>.</p>

                <div id="gatekeeping-popup" class="popup">
                    <span class="popup-close">&times;</span>
                    <div class="definition-term">Professional Gatekeeping</div>
                    <p><strong>Gatekeeping</strong> means controlling who gets to enter a profession. Professional associations did this by:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Setting standards</strong>: requiring specific degrees, exams, and training</li>
                        <li><strong>Credentialing</strong>: issuing licenses and certifications</li>
                        <li><strong>Excluding</strong>: denying membership to women and minorities</li>
                    </ul>
                    <h4>The Paradox:</h4>
                    <p>These organizations genuinely improved professional quality ‚Äî medical training got better, legal standards became more uniform. But they also closed ranks against women and people of color. Elizabeth Blackwell had been admitted to medical school as early as 1849, but as separate medical colleges gave way to university medical schools in the late 1800s, women actually <em>lost</em> ground.</p>

                    <h4>Why This Matters for Progressivism:</h4>
                    <p>College-educated women who couldn't join professional associations needed somewhere to direct their training and ambition. Reform movements ‚Äî settlement houses, women's clubs, public health campaigns ‚Äî became that outlet.</p>
                </div>

                <aside class="notes">
                    <h4>üìö What You Need to Know</h4>
                    <p>The key point isn't just that these organizations existed ‚Äî it's that they were all-white and all-male. This created a specific kind of frustration for educated women: they had the training but not the access. The professions said "you're not welcome." Reform said "we need you."</p>

                    <h4>üéì Historians Weigh In</h4>
                    <p><strong>Robert Wiebe</strong> in <em>The Search for Order</em> argues that the rise of professions was central to the Progressive movement. The same impulse that created professional standards ‚Äî the belief that expertise could solve problems ‚Äî also drove Progressive reform. Progressives were, in many ways, professionals looking for problems to professionalize.</p>
                </aside>
            </section>

            <!-- ========== SLIDE 8: The Structural Insight ========== -->
            <section>
                <h2>The Structural Insight</h2>
                <div class="callout">
                    <div class="callout-title">üîë Why Progressivism Happened <em>When</em> It Did</div>
                    <p>It wasn't just that problems existed ‚Äî problems always existed.</p>
                    <p style="margin-top: 0.5em;">A <span class="key-term">new class</span> with education, professional training, and frustrated ambitions needed somewhere to direct that energy.</p>
                </div>
                <p style="margin-top: 1.5em;">Reform became their vehicle:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>The <span class="key-term">settlement house</span> wasn't charity ‚Äî it was a career path for women who couldn't get hired</li>
                    <li>The <span class="key-term">muckraking article</span> wasn't just journalism ‚Äî it was a profession made possible by cheap magazines paying real money</li>
                    <li>The <span class="key-term">social survey</span> wasn't just data ‚Äî it was social science seeking institutional authority</li>
                </ul>

                <aside class="notes">
                    <h4>üìö What You Need to Know</h4>
                    <p>This is the analytical core of Part I. Students need to understand that Progressivism wasn't just a moral awakening ‚Äî it was a structural phenomenon. A new class created by the Gilded Age economy needed outlets. The problems were real, but the movement was possible because the right people existed at the right time with the right frustrations.</p>

                    <h4>üí≠ Context & Connections</h4>
                    <p>This framing helps students think structurally about reform movements in general. Why do some reform movements succeed and others fail? Often the answer has less to do with the severity of the problem and more to do with whether a class of people with resources and motivation exists to address it.</p>
                </aside>
            </section>

            <!-- ========== PAUSE & PROCESS 1 ========== -->
            <section class="assessment-slide">
                <h2>‚è∏Ô∏è Pause &amp; Process</h2>
                <div class="assessment-prompt">
                    <h3 style="color: var(--antique-gold);">What Made Progressivism Possible?</h3>
                    <p style="margin-top: 1em;">What made progressivism possible as a <em>movement</em> ‚Äî the problems it addressed, or the class of people with the resources to address them?</p>
                </div>

                <aside class="notes">
                    <h4>üéØ Teaching Note</h4>
                    <p>This is designed to provoke. Most students will instinctively say "the problems." Push them: problems existed for decades before Progressivism. What changed wasn't the problems ‚Äî it was the people. The expansion of higher education, the rise of professions, and the frustration of educated women created a class that needed reform as much as reform needed them.</p>
                    <p>The best answer acknowledges both: you need real problems AND people with resources. But the structural insight is that the timing depended on the class, not the crisis.</p>
                </aside>
            </section>

            <!-- ========== PART II DIVIDER ========== -->
            <section class="section-divider">
                <h2>Part II</h2>
                <h3 style="color: var(--deep-teal);">What Was Progressivism?</h3>
                <p style="color: #aaa; font-style: italic;">Defining the movement and its entry points</p>
            </section>

            <!-- ========== SLIDE 11: Defining Progressivism ========== -->
            <section>
                <h2>What Was Progressivism?</h2>
                <p>A reform movement that believed <span class="key-term">activist government</span> could right political, economic, and social wrongs.</p>
                <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 1.5em; margin-top: 1em;">
                    <div class="comparison-box">
                        <h3>The Old View</h3>
                        <p>Centralized government is the <span class="key-term">enemy</span> of liberty.</p>
                        <p style="font-size: 0.85em; margin-top: 0.5em; color: #aaa;">Americans had long distrusted federal power. The Populists challenged this but were defeated.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="comparison-box alt">
                        <h3>The Progressive View</h3>
                        <p>Strong government is the <span class="key-term">protector</span> of liberty.</p>
                        <p style="font-size: 0.85em; margin-top: 0.5em; color: #aaa;">Progressives had to rebuild the case for government as a force for good.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <aside class="notes">
                    <h4>üìö What You Need to Know</h4>
                    <p>This is the single most important conceptual shift of the Progressive Era. For most of American history, Americans saw government ‚Äî especially the federal government ‚Äî as a threat to individual freedom. The Founders designed the Constitution to limit government power. Progressives flipped that: they argued that without government intervention, corporations and corruption would destroy liberty. Government wasn't the problem ‚Äî it was the solution.</p>

                    <h4>üí≠ The Tension Within</h4>
                    <p>Not all progressives agreed on how far this should go. Some wanted temporary government action: clean up corruption, bust the trusts, then step back. Others wanted a permanently active government with power to tax income, regulate industry, protect consumers, empower workers, and provide social welfare. This split would define American politics for the rest of the 20th century.</p>
                </aside>
            </section>

            <!-- ========== SLIDE 12: Scaling the Template ========== -->
            <section>
                <h2>Scaling the Sanitary Reform Template</h2>
                <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr auto 1fr; gap: 1em; align-items: center;">
                    <div class="comparison-box" style="font-size: 0.85em;">
                        <h3>Sanitary Reform<br><small>(1870s‚Äì1890s)</small></h3>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Problem: Cholera, typhoid</li>
                            <li>Method: Map disease, investigate water</li>
                            <li>Solution: Boards of health, quarantine</li>
                            <li>Scope: <span class="key-term">Urban sanitation</span></li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div style="font-size: 2em; color: var(--antique-gold);">‚Üí</div>
                    <div class="comparison-box alt" style="font-size: 0.85em;">
                        <h3>Progressivism<br><small>(1890s‚Äì1920s)</small></h3>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Problem: All industrial-era problems</li>
                            <li>Method: Muckraking, social surveys, moral crusade</li>
                            <li>Solution: Regulatory agencies, labor laws, constitutional amendments</li>
                            <li>Scope: <span class="key-term">Entire society</span></li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <p style="margin-top: 1em; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.95em;">Same playbook. National scale.</p>

                <aside class="notes">
                    <h4>üìö What You Need to Know</h4>
                    <p>This comparison makes the Chapter 20 connection explicit. The sanitary reformers invented the progressive method ‚Äî investigation, expertise, government intervention ‚Äî but only applied it to public health. Progressives took that exact template and applied it to everything: labor conditions, food safety, political corruption, vice, poverty, even human reproduction (which we'll see in Lectures 2 and 3).</p>
                </aside>
            </section>

            <!-- ========== SLIDE 13: Young Protestants ========== -->
            <section>
                <h2>Entry Point 1: Young Protestants</h2>
                <p>Many progressives were raised in homes where <span class="key-term">religious conviction spurred social action</span>.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Expected to become ministers or missionaries ‚Äî redirected that moral energy toward reform</li>
                    <li><span class="popup-trigger" data-popup="socialgospel-popup">Social Gospel</span> (Walter Rauschenbusch): Christianity demands work for the social good</li>
                    <li>Billy Sunday: elevated anti-saloon crusade into righteous warfare</li>
                    <li>William Jennings Bryan: bridged Populism and Progressivism, insisted Christian piety and democracy were inseparable</li>
                </ul>

                <div id="socialgospel-popup" class="popup">
                    <span class="popup-close">&times;</span>
                    <div class="definition-term">The Social Gospel</div>
                    <p>A movement within Protestant Christianity that argued faith required addressing <strong>social sin</strong>, not just individual sin.</p>
                    <h4>Core Idea:</h4>
                    <p>If social structures (low wages, unsafe housing, exploitative labor) caused suffering, then Christians had a <em>duty</em> to reform those structures. Building the Kingdom of God meant creating a just society on Earth.</p>
                    <h4>Key Figure:</h4>
                    <p><strong>Walter Rauschenbusch</strong>, a Baptist minister whose <em>Christianity and the Social Crisis</em> (1907) became the movement's manifesto. He argued that individual salvation was not enough ‚Äî society itself needed to be redeemed.</p>
                    <h4>Why It Mattered:</h4>
                    <p>The Social Gospel made Progressive reform seem like Christian duty rather than radical politics. If helping the poor was what Jesus commanded, then government intervention was morally legitimate.</p>
                    <h4>Limits:</h4>
                    <p>Primarily a white, Protestant movement. Catholic and African American churches developed parallel social reform traditions but faced exclusion from white Progressive networks.</p>
                </div>

                <aside class="notes">
                    <h4>üìö What You Need to Know</h4>
                    <p>The Protestant moral energy behind Progressivism is crucial for understanding both its power and its limits. The same moral certainty that drove reformers to help the poor also led them to impose their values on communities whose habits they disapproved of ‚Äî drinking, dancing, sexual freedom. This tension runs through the entire unit.</p>
                </aside>
            </section>

            <!-- ========== SLIDE 14: Muckrakers ========== -->
            <section>
                <h2>Entry Point 2: Muckrakers</h2>
                <p>Investigative journalists determined to dredge up the <span class="key-term">"muck"</span> saturating American institutions:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Ida Tarbell</strong> ‚Äî exposed Standard Oil's monopoly practices</li>
                    <li><strong>Lincoln Steffens</strong> ‚Äî unraveled municipal corruption</li>
                    <li><strong>George Kibbe Turner</strong> ‚Äî documented prostitution in ethnic neighborhoods</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top: 1em;">The delivery system: cheap <span class="popup-trigger" data-popup="magazines-popup">10-cent magazines</span> with circulations up to 1 million</p>
                <div class="callout" style="margin-top: 1em;">
                    <div class="callout-title">üîë The Strategy</div>
                    <p>Shock the public into recognition, then prompt "the people" to demand change. <span class="key-term">Exposure</span> as political tool.</p>
                </div>

                <div id="magazines-popup" class="popup">
                    <span class="popup-close">&times;</span>
                    <div class="definition-term">The Magazine Revolution</div>
                    <p>Cheap 10-cent periodicals like <strong>McClure's Magazine</strong> and <strong>Ladies' Home Journal</strong> displaced expensive 35-cent publications like <em>Harper's</em> and <em>The Atlantic Monthly</em>.</p>
                    <h4>What This Changed:</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Wider readership</strong>: Circulations reached 400,000 to 1 million</li>
                        <li><strong>Better pay</strong>: Attracted talented, ambitious journalists</li>
                        <li><strong>Receptive publishers</strong>: Sensational expos√©s sold copies</li>
                    </ul>
                    <h4>Why It Matters:</h4>
                    <p>Muckraking wasn't just moral conviction ‚Äî it was a <em>business model</em>. Cheap magazines created a mass audience, and publishers learned that investigative stories sold. This made reform journalism economically viable for the first time.</p>
                </div>

                <aside class="notes">
                    <h4>üìö What You Need to Know</h4>
                    <p>Muckraking was both a moral crusade and a media business. The expansion of cheap magazines created the infrastructure for investigative journalism. This connects to the new middle class: journalism became a profession that paid well enough to attract educated, ambitious people. Between 1902 and 1916, more than 100 cities launched investigations of the prostitution trade ‚Äî largely because muckrakers had made these issues front-page news.</p>

                    <h4>üí≠ Context & Connections</h4>
                    <p>Compare to the sanitary reformers: both used investigation and exposure. But muckrakers had mass media. Their reach was national, not local. This is what scaled the progressive template.</p>
                </aside>
            </section>

            <!-- ========== SLIDE 15: Settlement Houses ========== -->
            <section>
                <h2>Entry Point 3: Settlement Houses and Clubwomen</h2>
                <p><span class="popup-trigger" data-popup="hullhouse-popup">Jane Addams</span> and Ellen Gates Starr founded Hull House in Chicago (1889):</p>
                <ul style="font-size: 0.9em;">
                    <li>Nursery, employment bureau, baby clinic, penny savings bank</li>
                    <li>Orchestra, reading groups, lecture series</li>
                    <li><strong>Florence Kelley</strong> became Illinois's chief factory inspector ‚Äî pushed through the state's first factory law</li>
                    <li><strong>Julia Lathrop</strong>, Edith Abbott, Sophonisba Breckinridge established social work as a discipline</li>
                    <li><strong>Alice Hamilton</strong> pioneered public health research</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top: 0.8em;">By 1910: over <span class="key-term">400 settlement houses</span> nationwide</p>

                <div id="hullhouse-popup" class="popup">
                    <span class="popup-close">&times;</span>
                    <div class="definition-term">Hull House and Jane Addams</div>
                    <p>In 1889, Jane Addams and Ellen Gates Starr bought a decaying mansion that had once been the country home of Charles J. Hull. By then, the neighborhood was surrounded by factories, churches, saloons, and tenements inhabited by poor, largely foreign-born working-class families.</p>
                    <h4>What Made Hull House Different:</h4>
                    <p>Addams <strong>moved in</strong> and demanded others who worked there do the same. This wasn't charity at a distance ‚Äî it was living among the people you were trying to help. The reformers studied the community from the inside.</p>
                    <h4>Who Came Through Hull House:</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>John Dewey</strong> taught philosophy</li>
                        <li><strong>Frank Lloyd Wright</strong> lectured on architecture</li>
                        <li><strong>Clarence Darrow</strong> (the workingman's lawyer) spent considerable time there</li>
                    </ul>
                    <h4>The Career Path:</h4>
                    <p>For college-educated women locked out of the professions, settlement houses were where they could use their training. Florence Kelley's factory investigations led to actual legislation. Julia Lathrop's research led to the U.S. Children's Bureau. The settlement house was a laboratory, a career, and a political base.</p>
                </div>

                <aside class="notes">
                    <h4>üìö What You Need to Know</h4>
                    <p>Settlement houses connect directly to the "new middle class" section. These women had professional training and nowhere to put it. Hull House wasn't just helping the poor ‚Äî it was building an alternative career track for women excluded from male-dominated professions. The fact that Kelley became a state factory inspector shows how reform became a pipeline to actual governmental power.</p>

                    <h4>üí≠ Context & Connections</h4>
                    <p>Black clubwomen drew on extensive experience in church organizations and Republican aid societies. In southern states, as black men were stripped of voting rights, jury service, and political office, black women stepped into the breach, providing indispensable services and leadership. They shared some conservative sentiments with white clubwomen on issues like alcohol and sexuality, but they also ventured into community affairs more boldly than their white counterparts.</p>
                </aside>
            </section>

            <!-- ========== SLIDE 16: Clubwomen ========== -->
            <section>
                <h2>The Women's Club Network</h2>
                <p>Hundreds of thousands of women organized through local clubs to:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Improve schools, build libraries and playgrounds</li>
                    <li>Expand educational and vocational opportunities for girls</li>
                    <li>Secure fire and sanitation codes for tenement houses</li>
                </ul>
                <div class="callout" style="margin-top: 1em;">
                    <div class="callout-title">üîë The Strategy</div>
                    <p>They made traditional female concerns ‚Äî nurturing children, caring for the home ‚Äî into questions of <span class="key-term">public policy</span>.</p>
                </div>
                <p style="margin-top: 1em; font-size: 0.9em; color: #aaa;">From Sorosis (1860s) to a vast national network by 1900 ‚Äî an enormous reserve army of activists.</p>

                <aside class="notes">
                    <h4>üìö What You Need to Know</h4>
                    <p>Women's clubs were distinct from antebellum moral reform societies. They were secular and had varied purposes, from intellectual discussion to civic reform. By the turn of the century, this network was vast and increasingly drawn to the efforts of Jane Addams and other female reformers to break down barriers excluding women from the public sphere.</p>

                    <h4>üí≠ Context & Connections</h4>
                    <p>Professional women who joined clubs weren't content to make them refuges from the male world. They were determined to use them to establish new channels for deploying their talents and exercising influence. This connects to the "frustrated ambitions" theme: the clubs were another outlet for educated women shut out of the professions.</p>
                </aside>
            </section>

