                <aside class="notes">
                    <h4>üìö What You Need to Know</h4>
                    <p>Sinclair was a committed socialist. His goal was to generate class consciousness ‚Äî to make middle-class readers care about immigrant workers' suffering. The novel follows Jurgis Rudkus, a Lithuanian immigrant, as the meatpacking industry destroys him and his family: dangerous work, poverty wages, sickness, death, corruption. Sinclair wanted readers to see capitalism itself as the villain.</p>

                    <h4>üí≠ Context & Connections</h4>
                    <p>The Chapter 20 callback matters here. Students studied these immigrant communities ‚Äî chain migration, ethnic enclaves, diaspora networks. Now they're seeing those same communities from inside the industrial machine that exploited them.</p>
                </aside>
            </section>

            <!-- ========== SLIDE 19: What Sinclair Described ========== -->
            <section>
                <h2>What Sinclair Described</h2>
                <div class="primary-source">
                    <p>"There would be meat stored in great piles in rooms; and the water from leaky roofs would drip over it, and thousands of rats would race about on it... A man could run his hand over these piles of meat and sweep off handfuls of the dried dung of rats."</p>
                    <div class="primary-source-attribution">‚Äî Upton Sinclair, <em>The Jungle</em> (1906)</div>
                </div>
                <p style="margin-top: 1.5em;">Sinclair described <strong>both</strong>:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Workers crushed by dangerous machinery, poisoned by chemicals, discarded when injured</li>
                    <li>Diseased cattle, chemical adulterants, rats ground into sausage</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top: 1em; font-style: italic;">The public focused on <span class="key-term">one</span> of these. Guess which.</p>

                <aside class="notes">
                    <h4>üìö What You Need to Know</h4>
                    <p>Sinclair devoted the vast majority of the book to the human story ‚Äî the immigrant family's slow destruction by capitalism. But readers skimmed over the workers' suffering and fixated on the food contamination chapters. Rats in sausage. Diseased cattle. Workers falling into rendering vats and being processed into lard. These images were visceral, intimate threats to readers' own bodies.</p>
                </aside>
            </section>

            <!-- ========== SLIDE 20: Why the Stomach Won ========== -->
            <section>
                <h2>Why the Stomach Won</h2>
                <div class="callout">
                    <div class="callout-title">üîë The Analytical Center</div>
                    <p>Why did Americans respond to <span class="key-term">tainted sausage</span> but not to <span class="key-term">crushed workers</span>?</p>
                </div>
                <p style="margin-top: 1.5em;">Remember the cholera logic from Chapter 20:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Cholera got results because disease <span class="key-term">crossed class lines</span> ‚Äî it could kill rich people too</li>
                    <li>Food contamination worked the same way ‚Äî <span class="key-term">anyone</span> could eat a bad sausage</li>
                    <li>Worker exploitation only hurt <span class="key-term">workers</span> ‚Äî and immigrant workers at that</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top: 1em; font-size: 1.05em;">Whose suffering registers as a political emergency depends on <span class="key-term">class, race, and nativity</span>.</p>

                <aside class="notes">
                    <h4>üìö What You Need to Know</h4>
                    <p>This is the analytical core of the lecture. The cholera parallel is exact: sanitary reformers got action because disease threatened everyone regardless of class. Food contamination created the same dynamic. But labor exploitation only affected the working poor ‚Äî disproportionately immigrants ‚Äî and so it failed to generate the same urgency.</p>

                    <h4>üîë The Progressive Formula</h4>
                    <p>Reform succeeds when the threat crosses class lines. When suffering stays contained to the poor and foreign-born, the urgency disappears. This pattern explains why consumer protection passed quickly while labor reform took decades. It also helps explain the limits of Progressivism more broadly.</p>

                    <h4>üéì Historians Weigh In</h4>
                    <p><strong>Gabriel Kolko</strong> argues in <em>The Triumph of Conservatism</em> that Progressive regulation often served business interests by making capitalism more stable and legitimate ‚Äî not by empowering workers. Food safety regulation is a perfect example: it made the system safer for consumers while leaving labor conditions largely unchanged.</p>
                </aside>
            </section>

            <!-- ========== PAUSE & PROCESS 2 ========== -->
            <section class="assessment-slide">
                <h2>‚è∏Ô∏è Pause &amp; Process</h2>
                <div class="assessment-prompt">
                    <h3 style="color: var(--antique-gold);">When Does Reform Happen?</h3>
                    <p style="margin-top: 1em;">The cholera crisis got results because disease threatened everyone.</p>
                    <p><em>The Jungle</em> got results because food threatened everyone.</p>
                    <p style="margin-top: 1em; font-size: 1.1em;">What kinds of suffering <strong>don't</strong> produce reform ‚Äî and why?</p>
