                <aside class="notes">
                    <h4>üéØ Teaching Note</h4>
                    <p>This is a discussion question, not a quiz. Let students wrestle with it. Push them toward the structural answer: suffering that stays contained to marginalized groups ‚Äî the poor, immigrants, racial minorities ‚Äî doesn't generate the same political urgency as suffering that threatens the middle class. This isn't because people are evil; it's because political systems respond to perceived threats to those with political power.</p>
                    <p>If students bring up modern examples (Flint water crisis, COVID disparities, etc.), let them run with it. The pattern is persistent.</p>
                </aside>
            </section>

            <!-- ========== SLIDE 22: Legislative Response ========== -->
            <section>
                <h2>The Legislative Response</h2>
                <p>Public outrage produced swift action:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><span class="key-term">Pure Food and Drug Act</span> (1906) ‚Äî prohibited adulterated or misbranded food and drugs</li>
                    <li><span class="key-term">Meat Inspection Act</span> (1906) ‚Äî mandated federal inspection of meatpacking plants</li>
                </ul>
                <div class="callout" style="margin-top: 1.5em;">
                    <div class="callout-title">üîë Notice What Got Fixed</div>
                    <p>Consumer protection ‚Äî protecting <span class="key-term">buyers</span>.</p>
                    <p style="margin-top: 0.3em;">Not labor reform ‚Äî protecting <span class="key-term">workers</span>.</p>
                </div>
                <p style="margin-top: 1em; font-size: 0.9em; color: #aaa;">Federal child labor laws were struck down by the Supreme Court in 1918 and 1922. Permanent labor protections didn't arrive until the 1930s.</p>

                <aside class="notes">
                    <h4>üìö What You Need to Know</h4>
                    <p>Both acts passed within months of <em>The Jungle</em>'s publication. President Theodore Roosevelt sent investigators to Chicago who confirmed Sinclair's allegations. The speed of legislative action shows how powerful the food safety issue was ‚Äî and, by contrast, how little political urgency attached to workers' conditions.</p>

                    <h4>üîë The Larger Point</h4>
                    <p>This is consumer protection as the progressive sweet spot. The federal government used the Commerce Clause to justify intervention in the food industry ‚Äî a huge expansion of federal power. But it was power exercised on behalf of consumers, not workers. The pattern: reforms that stabilize capitalism succeed; reforms that challenge it don't.</p>
                </aside>
            </section>

            <!-- ========== SLIDE 23: Addams and the Limits of Sympathy ========== -->
            <section>
                <h2>Addams and the Limits of Sympathy</h2>
                <p>Jane Addams was <span class="key-term">more sympathetic</span> toward immigrants than most reformers:</p>
                <ul style="font-size: 0.9em;">
                    <li>Respected their cultural inheritance</li>
                    <li>Encouraged them to integrate <span class="popup-trigger" data-popup="gifts-popup">"immigrant gifts"</span> into new identities</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top: 1em;">But there were limits:</p>
                <ul style="font-size: 0.9em;">
                    <li>Opposed <span class="key-term">saloons</span> ‚Äî ignoring their role as informal banks, meeting halls, and community spaces</li>
                    <li>Disapproved of <span class="key-term">working-class entertainments</span> that gave young people unregulated intimacy</li>
                    <li>Worried the <span class="key-term">sexual revolution</span> would drive poor women into prostitution</li>
                </ul>

                <div id="gifts-popup" class="popup">
                    <span class="popup-close">&times;</span>
                    <div class="definition-term">"Immigrant Gifts"</div>
                    <p>Addams's idea that immigrants brought valuable cultural traditions ‚Äî music, crafts, cooking, communal practices ‚Äî that should be incorporated into American life, not erased.</p>
                    <h4>This Was Unusual:</h4>
                    <p>Most progressive reformers wanted immigrants to assimilate completely ‚Äî to become "100% American" by abandoning their old customs. Addams took a more pluralistic view: America would be enriched by cultural diversity, not threatened by it.</p>
                    <h4>But There Were Limits:</h4>
                    <p>Addams's respect for immigrant culture didn't extend to everything. She drew the line at practices she considered harmful: saloon culture, unregulated courtship, gambling. Other reformers went further, considering many immigrants "culturally, even racially, inferior." Addams was better than most ‚Äî but she still wanted to manage immigrant communities in ways that reflected her own middle-class Protestant values.</p>
                </div>

                <aside class="notes">
                    <h4>üìö What You Need to Know</h4>
                    <p>This slide establishes the core tension of Progressivism: reformers who genuinely cared about the poor but also wanted to manage them. Addams is the best case ‚Äî more sympathetic than most. But even she imposed her values on communities whose actual needs she didn't fully understand.</p>

                    <h4>üí≠ The Saloon Example</h4>
                    <p>On Chicago's South Side, saloons provided food, meeting space for fraternal organizations, and camaraderie to men longing to speak in their native tongue. Saloonkeepers functioned as informal bankers, cashing checks and making small loans. When progressives shut down saloons, they destroyed community infrastructure without replacing it. Not surprisingly, many immigrants shunned the prohibition movement.</p>

                    <h4>üîó The Prohibition Thread</h4>
                    <p>Addams and other settlement workers joined the WCTU (245,000 members by 1911) and the Anti-Saloon League to push for prohibition. By 1916, 16 states banned alcohol. By 1919, the Eighteenth Amendment made it national. Prohibition is a progressive reform ‚Äî driven by the same impulse to manage social life through legislation.</p>
                </aside>
            </section>

            <!-- ========== SLIDE 24: The Pattern ========== -->
            <section>
                <h2>The Pattern</h2>
                <p style="margin-bottom: 1em;">Return to the Chapter 20 framework:</p>
                <div style="display: flex; justify-content: center; align-items: center; gap: 0.5em; font-size: 1.1em; flex-wrap: wrap;">
                    <span style="color: var(--antique-gold); font-weight: 700;">Crisis</span>
                    <span style="color: #aaa;">‚Üí</span>
                    <span style="color: var(--antique-gold); font-weight: 700;">Intervention</span>
                    <span style="color: #aaa;">‚Üí</span>
                    <span style="color: var(--antique-gold); font-weight: 700;">Institutionalization</span>
                    <span style="color: #aaa;">‚Üí</span>
                    <span style="color: var(--antique-gold); font-weight: 700;">Expansion</span>
                </div>
                <p style="margin-top: 1.5em;">Sanitary reform created <span class="key-term">boards of health</span>.</p>
                <p>Progressivism creates the <span class="key-term">FDA</span>, factory inspection, the income tax, the Federal Reserve.</p>
                <p style="margin-top: 1.5em;">The state is growing ‚Äî and the progressive faith in <span class="key-term">expertise and government power</span> is growing with it.</p>
                <div class="callout" style="margin-top: 1em;">
                    <div class="callout-title">üîë The Question That Drives This Unit</div>
                    <p>This is <em>their</em> state ‚Äî built by professionals, credentialed experts, college-educated reformers.</p>
                    <p style="margin-top: 0.3em;">Who benefits from that power, and who gets <span class="key-term">controlled</span> by it?</p>
                </div>

                <aside class="notes">
                    <h4>üìö What You Need to Know</h4>
                    <p>This connects the middle-class section from Part I to the pattern section. The new middle class built the progressive state ‚Äî and it was a state that reflected their values, their expertise, their priorities. The FDA protects consumers (them). Factory inspection manages workers (not them). The question of who benefits and who gets controlled becomes central in Lectures 2 and 3, when progressives turn from managing systems to managing bodies.</p>
                </aside>
            </section>

            <!-- ========== SLIDE 25: Bridge ========== -->
            <section>
                <h2>Looking Forward</h2>
                <p>Today we met the progressives: a <span class="key-term">new middle class</span> with education, moral energy, and frustrated ambitions.</p>
                <p style="margin-top: 1em;">They built a reform movement on the sanitary reformers' template ‚Äî investigation, expertise, government power.</p>
                <p style="margin-top: 1em;">They fixed food. They exposed corruption. They built settlement houses.</p>
                <p style="margin-top: 1.5em;">But even in their best work, there was a tension:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>They wanted to <span class="key-term">help</span> the poor and <span class="key-term">manage</span> them</li>
                    <li>They respected immigrants and <span class="key-term">disapproved</span> of how they lived</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top: 1.5em; font-style: italic; color: var(--antique-gold);">Next time: progressives stop trying to fix <em>systems</em> and start trying to fix <em>people</em> ‚Äî their desires, their bodies, their reproduction.</p>

                <aside class="notes">
                    <h4>üìö What You Need to Know</h4>
                    <p>This bridge sets up the body-theme arc for the rest of the unit. Lecture 1 = body as victim (of industrial capitalism, contaminated food, exploitative labor). Lecture 2 = body as danger / autonomy (vice panics, policing desire, Sanger and birth control). Lecture 3 = body as state property (eugenics, sterilization, immigration restriction).</p>

                    <h4>üîó The Arc</h4>
                    <p>The progressive paradox: every tool they built to help people could also be used to control them. That tension doesn't resolve ‚Äî it intensifies across the next two lectures.</p>
                </aside>
            </section>

